gency that lies behind diverse forms of poetic difficulty--from Yeats's esoteric symbolism and Oppen's minimalism and silence to O'Hara's joyful slightness and the Language poets' rejection of traditional aesthetic satisfactions. For these poets, what begins as a practical question about the conduct of literary life--what distinguishes a poet or group of poets?--ends up as an ontological inquiry about social life: What is a person and how is a community possible? In the face of the violence and dislocation of the twentieth century, these poets resist their will to mastery, shy away from the sensual richness of their strongest work, and undermine the particularity of their imaginative and moral visions--all in an effort to allow personhood itself to emerge as an undeniable fact making an unrefusable claim.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aPoetry, Moderny20th centuryxHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh  aA. R. Ammons.  aAnglo-American poetry.  aBob Perelman.  aDiscrete Series.  aFrank O'Hara.  aGeorge Oppen.  aLanguage poetry.  aLeningrad.  aRobinson Crusoe.  aThe Materials.  aWilliam Butler Yeats.  aaesthetics.  acollective intention.  acollectivity.  acompleteness.  aconversation.  acounterfactual identity.  acultural determinism.  aethics.  aeugenics.  afreedom.  agrammaticality.  ainattention.  ainterpretation.  ajudgment.  aliterary life.  alove.  aminimalism.  aparticularity.  aperfection.  aperson.  apersonhood.  apoem.  apoet.  apoetic agency.  apoetic community.  apoetic difficulty.  apoetic knowledge.  apoetic mastery.  apoetic politics.  apoetry.  apreference.  areading.  asilence.  aslightness.  asocial life.  asocial recognition.  asymbolism.  atranslation.08iTitle is 